.TH ssl 3 "ssl 11.5.3" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
ssl \- Interface functions for TLS (Transport Layer Security) and DTLS (Datagram Transport Layer Security).

.SH DESCRIPTION
.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.RE

.PP
The application's name is still SSL because the first versions of the TLS protocol were named SSL (Secure Socket Layer). However, no version of the old SSL protocol is supported by this application.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> ssl:start(), ssl:connect("google.com", 443, [{verify, verify_peer},
    {cacerts, public_key:cacerts_get()}]).
{ok,{sslsocket, [...]}}

.fi

.PP
See Examples for detailed usage and more examples of this API.

.PP
Special Erlang node configuration for the application can be found in SSL Application.

.SH DATA TYPES
.LP
.B
\fBactive_msgs() ::\fR
\fB          {ssl, sslsocket(), Data :: binary() | list()} |\fR
\fB          {ssl_closed, sslsocket()} |\fR
\fB          {ssl_error,\fR
\fB           sslsocket(),\fR
\fB           Alert :: error_alert() | (Reason :: any())} |\fR
\fB          {ssl_passive, sslsocket()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The type for the messages that are delivered to the owner of a TLS/DTLS socket in active mode.

.PP
The \fIssl_error\fR reason may convey a TLS protocol alert if such an event occurs after the connection has been established. The most common case when this will happen is on the client side when a TLS-1.3 server requests a client certificate and the provided certificate is not accepted by the server, as it will be verified after the server has sent its last handshake message.

.PP
The \fIssl_passive\fR message is sent only when the socket is in \fI{active, N}\fR mode and the counter has dropped to 0. It indicates that the socket has transitioned to passive (\fI{active, false}\fR) mode.


.RE
.B
\fBanchor_fun() :: fun().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Claim an intermediate CA in the chain as trusted.

.IP
.nf
fun(Chain::[public_key:der_encoded()]) ->
      {trusted_ca, DerCert::public_key:der_encoded()} | unknown_ca.

.fi

.PP
TLS then uses \fIpublic_key:pkix_path_validation/3\fR with the selected CA as the trusted anchor and verifies the rest of the chain.


.RE
.B
\fBcert_key_conf() ::\fR
\fB          #{cert =>\fR
\fB                public_key:der_encoded() | [public_key:der_encoded()],\fR
\fB            key => key(),\fR
\fB            certfile => file:filename(),\fR
\fB            keyfile => file:filename(),\fR
\fB            password => iodata() | fun(() -> iodata())}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Configuration of the entity certificate and its corresponding key.

.PP
A certificate (or possibly a list including the certificate and its chain certificates, where the entity certificate must be the first element in the list or the first entry in the file) and its associated key. For the PEM file format, there can also be a password associated with the file containing the key.

.PP
For maximum interoperability, the certificates in the chain should be in the correct order, as the chain will be sent as-is to the peer. If chain certificates are not provided, certificates from the configured trusted CA certificates will be used to construct the chain. See \fIclient_option_cert()\fR and \fIserver_option_cert()\fR for more information.


.RE
.B
\fBcipher() ::\fR
\fB          aes_256_gcm | aes_128_gcm | aes_256_ccm | aes_128_ccm |\fR
\fB          chacha20_poly1305 | aes_256_ccm_8 | aes_128_ccm_8 |\fR
\fB          aes_128_cbc | aes_256_cbc |\fR
\fB          legacy_cipher().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Cipher algorithms that can be used for payload encryption.


.RE
.B
\fBcipher_filters() ::\fR
\fB          [{key_exchange | cipher | mac | prf,\fR
\fB            fun((kex_algo() | cipher() | hash() | aead | default_prf) ->\fR
\fB                    true | false)}].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Filter that allows you to customize cipher suite list.


.RE
.B
\fBcipher_suites() :: ciphers().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A list of cipher suites that should be supported.

.PP
Function ssl:cipher_suites/2  can be used to find all cipher suites that are supported by default and all cipher suites that can be configured.

.PP
If you compose your own \fIcipher_suites/0\fR make sure they are filtered for crypto library support using ssl:filter_cipher_suites/2 .

.PP
The following function can help creating customized cipher suite lists:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
ssl:append_cipher_suites/2 

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
ssl:prepend_cipher_suites/2

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
ssl:suite_to_str/1

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
ssl:str_to_suite/1

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
ssl:suite_to_openssl_str/1

.RE

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.RE

.PP
Note that TLS-1.3 and TLS-1.2 use different sets of cipher suites. To support both versions, cipher suites from both sets need to be included. If the supplied list does not comply with the configured versions or crypto library, that is, resulting in an empty list, the option will fall back to its appropriate default value for the configured versions.

.PP
Non-default cipher suites, including anonymous cipher suites (prior to TLS 1.3), are supported for interoperability and testing purposes. These can be used by adding them to your cipher suite list. Note that they also need to be supported and enabled by the peer to be actually used, and they may require additional configuration; see \fIsrp_param_type()\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBciphers() :: [erl_cipher_suite()] | string().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Cipher suite formats.

.PP
For backwards compatibility, cipher suites can be configured as a colon-separated string of cipher suite RFC names (or even old OpenSSL names). However, a more flexible approach is to use utility functions together with \fIcipher_filters()\fR if a customized cipher suite option is needed.


.RE
.B
\fBclient_option() ::\fR
\fB          client_option_cert() |\fR
\fB          common_option_cert() |\fR
\fB          {psk_groups, [group()]} |\fR
\fB          {alpn_advertised_protocols,\fR
\fB           AppProtocols :: [AppProto :: binary()]} |\fR
\fB          {max_fragment_length,\fR
\fB           MaxLen :: undefined | 512 | 1024 | 2048 | 4096} |\fR
\fB          client_option_tls13() |\fR
\fB          common_option_tls13() |\fR
\fB          client_option_pre_tls13() |\fR
\fB          common_option_pre_tls13() |\fR
\fB          common_option_dtls() |\fR
\fB          client_option_legacy() |\fR
\fB          common_option_legacy().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The following options are specific to the client side, or have different semantics for the client and server:

{psk_groups, Groups}
.RS 2
key exchange groups that the client will send pre share keys for, defaults to first group in supported_groups. Must be a subset of supported_groups and will be sent in the same order as they appear in supported_groups.


.RE

{alpn_advertised_protocols, AppProtocols}
.RS 2
Application layer protocol

.PP
The list of protocols supported by the client to be sent to the server to be used for an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN). If the server supports ALPN, it will choose a protocol from this list; otherwise it will fail the connection with a \fIno_application_protocol\fR alert. A server that does not support ALPN will ignore this value. The list of protocols must not contain an empty binary.


.RE

{max_fragment_length, MaxLen}
.RS 2
Max fragment length extension

.PP
Specifies the maximum fragment length the client is prepared to accept from the server. See RFC 6066.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBclient_option_cert() ::\fR
\fB          {verify, Verify :: verify_peer | verify_none} |\fR
\fB          {cacerts,\fR
\fB           CACerts ::\fR
\fB               [public_key:der_encoded()] | [public_key:combined_cert()]} |\fR
\fB          {cacertfile, CACertFile :: file:filename()} |\fR
\fB          {server_name_indication, SNI :: inet:hostname() | disable} |\fR
\fB          {customize_hostname_check, HostNameCheckOpts :: list()} |\fR
\fB          {certificate_authorities, boolean()} |\fR
\fB          {stapling, Stapling :: staple | no_staple | map()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Certificate-related options specific to the client side, or with different semantics for the client and server.

{verify, Verify}
.RS 2
Verification of certificates

.PP
This option specifies whether certificates are to be verified.

.PP
If \fIVerify\fR is \fIverify_peer\fR, which is the default, it is required to also provide one of the options \fIcacerts\fR or \fIcacertfile\fR in order for the certificate verification to succeed. For example, an HTTPS client can use option \fI{cacerts, public_key:cacerts_get()}\fR to use the trusted CA certificates provided by the operating system.

.PP
If \fIVerify\fR is \fIverify_none\fR, all X.509-certificate path validation errors will be ignored.

.PP
\fBCHANGE: \fRThe default for \fIVerify\fR was changed to \fIverify_peer\fR in Erlang/OTP 26.



.RE

{cacerts, CACerts}
.RS 2
Trusted certificates

.PP
The DER-encoded trusted certificates. If this option is supplied it overrides option \fIcacertfile\fR.

.PP
Function \fIpublic_key:cacerts_get/0\fR can be used to retrieve to the trusted CA certificates provided by the operating system.


.RE

{cacertfile, CertFile}
.RS 2
End entity certificate

.PP
Path to a file containing PEM-encoded CA certificates. The CA certificates are used during server authentication and when building the client certificate chain.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRWhen PEM caching is enabled, files provided with this option will be checked for updates at fixed time intervals specified by the ssl_pem_cache_clean environment parameter.



.RE

{server_name_indication, SNI}
.RS 2
Server Name Indication extension

.PP
Specify the hostname to be used in TLS Server Name Indication extension. If not specified it will default to the \fIHost\fR argument of connect/3,4 unless it is of type \fIinet:ip_address()\fR. The hostname will also be used in the hostname verification of the peer certificate using \fIpublic_key:pkix_verify_hostname/2\fR. The special value \fIdisable\fR prevents the Server Name Indication extension from being sent and disables the hostname verification check.


.RE

{customize_hostname_check, HostNameCheckOpts}
.RS 2
Customization option

.PP
Customizes the hostname verification of the peer certificate, as various protocols that use TLS, such as HTTP or LDAP, may require different approaches. For example, here is how to use standard hostname checking for HTTPS implemented in Public_Key:

.IP
.nf
{customize_hostname_check, [{match_fun, public_key:pkix_verify_hostname_match_fun(https)}]}

.fi

.PP
For futher description of the customize options, see \fIpublic_key:pkix_verify_hostname/3\fR.


.RE

{client_certificate_authorities, UseCertAuth}
.RS 2
Inter-op hint option

.PP
If \fIUseCertAuth\fR is set to \fItrue\fR, sends the certificate authorities extension in the TLS-1.3 client hello. The default is \fIfalse\fR. Note that setting \fIUseCertAuth\fR to \fItrue\fR can result in a significant overhead if there exists many trusted CA certificates. (Since Erlang/OTP 24.3.)


.RE

{stapling, Stapling}
.RS 2
Certificate revocation check option

.PP
If \fIStapling\fR is atom \fIstaple\fR or a map, OCSP stapling will be enabled, meaning that an extension of type "status_request" will be included in the client hello to indicate the desire to receive certificate status information.

.PP
If \fIStapling\fR is set to \fIno_staple\fR (the default), OCSP stapling will be disabled.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fREven if requested by the client, the OCSP response might not be provided by the server. In such event, SSL will proceed with the handshake and generate a \fI{missing, stapling_response}\fR logger event.


.PP
When \fIStapling\fR is given as a map, boolean \fIocsp_nonce\fR key can indicate whether an OCSP nonce should be requested by the client (default is \fIfalse\fR).

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe OCSP response can be provided without a nonce value — even if it was requested by the client. In such cases SSL will proceed with the handshake and generate a \fI{missing, ocsp_nonce}\fR logger event.



.RE


.RE
.B
\fBclient_option_legacy() ::\fR
\fB          {client_preferred_next_protocols,\fR
\fB           NextAppProtocols ::\fR
\fB               {Precedence :: server | client,\fR
\fB                ClientPrefs :: [AppProto :: binary()]} |\fR
\fB               {Precedence :: server | client,\fR
\fB                ClientPrefs :: [AppProto :: binary()],\fR
\fB                Default :: (AppProto :: binary())}}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Legacy client options.

{client_preferred_next_protocols, NextAppProtocols}
.RS 2
Next Protocol Negotiation

.PP
ALPN (Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation) deprecates NPN (Next Protocol Negotiation) and this option.

.PP
Indicates that the client wants to perform Next Protocol Negotiation.

.PP
If \fIPrecedence\fR is \fIserver\fR, the negotiated protocol is the first protocol to be shown on the server advertised list that is also on the client preference list.

.PP
If \fIPrecedence\fR is \fIclient\fR, the negotiated protocol is the first protocol to be shown on the client preference list that is also on the server advertised list.

.PP
If the client does not support any of the server advertised protocols or the server does not advertise any protocols, the client falls back to the first protocol in its list or to the default protocol (if a default is supplied). If the server does not support Next Protocol Negotiation, the connection terminates if no default protocol is supplied.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBclient_option_pre_tls13() ::\fR
\fB          {reuse_session,\fR
\fB           SessionRef ::\fR
\fB               session_id() | {session_id(), SessionData :: binary()}} |\fR
\fB          {reuse_sessions, Reuse :: boolean() | save} |\fR
\fB          {psk_identity, PskID :: string()} |\fR
\fB          {srp_identity,\fR
\fB           SrpID :: {Username :: string(), Password :: string()}} |\fR
\fB          {fallback, LegacyFallback :: boolean()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Options only relevant to TLS versions prior to TLS-1.3.

{reuse_session, SessionRef}
.RS 2
Explicit session reuse

.PP
Reuses a specific session.

.PP
Since Erlang/OTP 21.3, if the session was saved earlier using option \fI{reuse_sessions, save}\fR, the session can be referred by its session ID.

.PP
Since Erlang/OTP 22.3, the session can be explicitly specified by its session ID and associated data.

.PP
See also SSL User's Guide, Session Reuse pre TLS 1.3.


.RE

{reuse_sessions, Reuse}
.RS 2
Enables later session reuse

.PP
When \fIReuse\fR is set to \fIsave\fR, a new connection will be negotiated and saved for later reuse. The session ID can be fetched with \fIconnection_information/2\fR and used with the client option \fIreuse_session\fR.

.PP
When \fIReuse\fR is set to \fItrue\fR, automated session reuse will be performed, if possible. If a new session is created, and is unique in regard to previous stored sessions, it will be saved for possible later reuse.

.PP
Since: OTP 21.3.


.RE

{psk_identity, PskID}
.RS 2
Option for use with PSK cipher suites

.PP
Specifies the identity the client presents to the server. The matching secret is found by the fun given in the \fIuser_lookup_fun\fR option.


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{srp_identity, SrpID}\fR\fR  - Option for use SRP cipher suites

.PP
Specifies the username and password to use to authenticate to the server.

.RE

{fallback, LegacyFallback}
.RS 2
Inter-op legacy client option

.PP
Send special cipher suite TLS_FALLBACK_SCSV to avoid an undesired TLS version downgrade. Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRThis option is not needed in normal TLS usage and must not be used to implement new clients. However, legacy clients that retries connections in the following manner: \fIssl:connect(Host, Port, [...{versions, ['tlsv2', 'tlsv1.1', 'tlsv1']}])\fR \fIssl:connect(Host, Port, [...{versions, [tlsv1.1', 'tlsv1']}, {fallback, true}])\fR \fIssl:connect(Host, Port, [...{versions, ['tlsv1']}, {fallback, true}])\fR can use it to avoid undesired TLS version downgrade. Note that TLS_FALLBACK_SCSV must also be supported by the server for the prevention to work.



.RE


.RE
.B
\fBclient_option_tls13() ::\fR
\fB          {session_tickets, SessionTickets :: disabled | manual | auto} |\fR
\fB          {use_ticket, Tickets :: [session_ticket()]} |\fR
\fB          {early_data, binary()} |\fR
\fB          {middlebox_comp_mode, MiddleBoxMode :: boolean()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Options only relevant for TLS-1.3.

{session_tickets, SessionTickets}
.RS 2
Use of session tickets

.PP
Configures the session ticket functionality. Allowed values are \fIdisabled\fR, \fImanual\fR, and \fIauto\fR. If it is set to \fImanual\fR the client will send the ticket information to user process in a 3-tuple:

.IP
.nf
{ssl, session_ticket, `Ticket::`(`t:session_ticket/0`)}

.fi

.PP
where \fITicket\fR is a map with information about the created TLS-1.3 session ticket. The only key that the user needs to consider is \fIsni\fR key to be able to provide it as a value in the use_ticket option list of possible tickets to use it to attempt session resumption to a server identified by the server name indication in \fImanual\fR session ticket mode.

.PP
If it is set to \fIauto\fR, the client automatically handles received tickets and tries to use them when making new TLS connections (session resumption with pre-shared keys).

.PP
Ticket lifetime, the number of tickets sent by the server, and the maximum number of tickets stored by the server in stateful mode are configured by application variables.

.PP
See also SSL User's Guide, Session Tickets and Session Resumption in TLS 1.3.


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{use_ticket, Tickets}\fR\fR

.PP
Configures the session tickets to be used for session resumption. It is a mandatory option in \fImanual\fR mode (\fI{session_tickets, manual}\fR).

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRSession tickets are only sent to the user if option \fIsession_tickets\fR is set to \fImanual\fR This option is supported by TLS-1.3. See also SSL User's Guide, Session Tickets and Session Resumption in TLS 1.3.


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{early_data, EarlyData}\fR\fR

.PP
Configures the early data to be sent by the client.

.PP
To verify that the server has the intention to process the early data, the following tuple is sent to the user process:

.IP
.nf
{ssl, SslSocket, {early_data, Result}}

.fi

.PP
where \fIResult\fR is either \fIaccepted\fR or \fIrejected\fR.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRIt is the responsibility of the user to handle rejected \fIEarlyData\fR and to resend when appropriate.


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{middlebox_comp_mode, MiddleBoxMode}\fR\fR

.PP
Configures the middlebox compatibility mode for a TLS-1.3 connection.

.PP
A significant number of middleboxes misbehave when a TLS-1.3 connection is negotiated. Implementations can increase the chance of making connections through those middleboxes by adapting the TLS-1.3 handshake to resemble that of a TLS-1.2 handshake.

.PP
The middlebox compatibility mode is enabled (\fItrue\fR) by default.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBcommon_option() ::\fR
\fB          {protocol, tls | dtls} |\fR
\fB          {handshake, hello | full} |\fR
\fB          {ciphers, cipher_suites()} |\fR
\fB          {signature_algs, signature_algs()} |\fR
\fB          {signature_algs_cert, [sign_scheme()]} |\fR
\fB          {keep_secrets,\fR
\fB           KeepSecrets ::\fR
\fB               boolean() |\fR
\fB               {keylog_hs, fun((Info :: keylog_info()) -> any())} |\fR
\fB               {keylog, fun((Info :: keylog_info()) -> any())}} |\fR
\fB          {max_handshake_size, HandshakeSize :: pos_integer()} |\fR
\fB          {versions, [protocol_version()]} |\fR
\fB          {log_level, Level :: logger:level() | none | all} |\fR
\fB          {hibernate_after, HibernateTimeout :: timeout()} |\fR
\fB          {receiver_spawn_opts,\fR
\fB           SpawnOpts :: [erlang:spawn_opt_option()]} |\fR
\fB          {sender_spawn_opts, SpawnOpts :: [erlang:spawn_opt_option()]}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Options common to both client and server side.

{protocol, Protocol}
.RS 2
Choose TLS or DTLS protocol for the transport layer security.

.PP
Defaults to \fItls\fR.


.RE

{handshake, Completion}
.RS 2
Possibly pause handshake at hello stage.

.PP
Defaults to \fIfull\fR. If \fIhello\fR is specified the handshake will pause after the hello message, allowing the user to make decisions based on hello extensions before continuing or aborting the handshake by calling \fIhandshake_continue/3\fR or \fIhandshake_cancel/1\fR.


.RE

{keep_secrets, KeepSecrets}
.RS 2
Configures a TLS connection for keylogging.

.PP
In order to be able retrieve all keylog information on a TLS connection, it must be configured in advance.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRThe keylog information defeats the purpose of the protocol and enabling it makes the user responsible for the information not ending up compromising security, it is intended for debugging.


.PP
The \fIkeep_secrets\fR functionality is disabled (\fIfalse\fR) by default. If set to legacy value \fItrue\fR keylog information can be retrieved from the connection using connection_information/2.

.PP
Added in OTP 23.2.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRNote that having to ask the connection has some drawbacks as for instance you can not get keylog information for failed connections, and other keylog items have to be retrieved in a polling manner and are not correctly formatted for key_updates.


.PP
Since OTP 27.3.1 you may instead of true provide a callback fun providing keylog information for either just failing handshakes or for entire connections, by setting \fIkeep_secrets\fR option to {keylog_hs, fun()} or {keylog, fun()}.  The fun is of arity one and will be called with keylog information \fIkeylog_info()\fR as an argument. \fIkeylog_hs fun\fR will only be called if the handshake fails, and is only relevant for \fITLS-1.3\fR that has encrypted messages before the first handshake is complete.\fIkeylog fun\fR will be called every time some secrets are updated and provide keylog for that update that is during the connection establishment and after that at \fIrenegotiation\fR or \fIkey update\fR (depending on TLS protocol version).  When a fun is used the connection_information/2 can not be used to retrieve key log information.  For more information see NSS keylog.


.RE

{max_handshake_size, HandshakeSize}
.RS 2
Limit the acceptable handshake packet size.

.PP
Used to limit the size of valid TLS handshake packets to avoid DoS attacks.

.PP
Integer (24 bits, unsigned). Defaults to \fI256*1024\fR before OTP-26 or if SLH-DSA algorithms are configured, otherwise the default is \fI256*1024\fR/2.


.RE

{hibernate_after, HibernateTimeout}
.RS 2
Hibernate inactive connection processes.

.PP
When an integer-value is specified, the TLS/DTLS connection goes into hibernation after the specified number of milliseconds of inactivity, thus reducing its memory footprint. When not specified the process never goes into hibernation.


.RE

{log_level, Level}
.RS 2
Specifies the log level for a TLS/DTLS connection.

.PP
Alerts are logged on \fInotice\fR level, which is the default level. The level \fIdebug\fR triggers verbose logging of TLS/DTLS protocol messages. See also SSL Application


.RE

{receiver|sender_spawn_opts, SpawnOpts}
.RS 2
Configure erlang spawn opts.

.PP
Configures spawn options of TLS sender and receiver processes.

.PP
Setting up garbage collection options can be helpful for trade-offs between CPU usage and memory usage. See \fIerlang:spawn_opt/2\fR.

.PP
For connections using Erlang distribution, the default sender option is \fI[...{priority, max}]\fR; this priority option cannot be changed. For all connections, \fI...link\fR is added to receiver and cannot be changed.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBcommon_option_cert() ::\fR
\fB          {certs_keys, CertsKeys :: [cert_key_conf()]} |\fR
\fB          {depth, AllowedCertChainLen :: pos_integer()} |\fR
\fB          {verify_fun,\fR
\fB           Verify :: {Verifyfun :: fun(), InitialUserState :: any()}} |\fR
\fB          {cert_policy_opts,\fR
\fB           PolicyOpts ::\fR
\fB               [{policy_set, [public_key:oid()]} |\fR
\fB                {explicit_policy, boolean()} |\fR
\fB                {inhibit_policy_mapping, boolean()} |\fR
\fB                {inhibit_any_policy, boolean()}]} |\fR
\fB          {allow_any_ca_purpose, Allow :: boolean()} |\fR
\fB          {crl_check, Check :: boolean() | peer | best_effort} |\fR
\fB          {crl_cache, crl_cache_opts()} |\fR
\fB          {partial_chain, anchor_fun()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Common certificate related options to both client and server.

{certs_keys, CertsKeys}
.RS 2
At least one certificate and key pair.

.PP
A list of a certificate (or possible a certificate and its chain) and the associated key of the certificate that can be used to authenticate the client or the server. The certificate key pair that is considered best and matches negotiated parameters for the connection will be selected.

.PP
The different signature algorithms are prioritized in the following order: \fIeddsa\fR, \fIecdsa\fR, \fIrsa_pss_pss\fR, \fIrsa\fR, and \fIdsa\fR. If more than one key is supplied for the same signature algorithm, they will be prioritized by strength (except for \fIengine keys\fR; see the next paragraph). This offers flexibility to, for instance, configure a newer certificate that is expected to be used in most cases, and an older but acceptable certificate that will only be used to communicate with legacy systems. Note that there is a trade off between the induced overhead and the flexibility; thus, alternatives should be chosen for good reasons.

.PP
\fIEngine keys\fR will be favored over other keys. As engine keys cannot be inspected, supplying more than one engine key makes no sense.

.PP
When this option is specified it overrides all single certificate and key options. For examples, see the User's Guide.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fR\fIeddsa\fR certificates are only supported by TLS-1.3 implementations that do not support \fIdsa\fR certificates. \fIrsa_pss_pss\fR (RSA certificates using Probabilistic Signature Scheme) are supported in TLS-1.2 and TLS-1.3, but some TLS-1.2 implementations do not support \fIrsa_pss_pss\fR.



.RE

{depth, AllowedCertChainLen}
.RS 2
Limits the accepted number of certificates in the certificate chain.

.PP
Maximum number of non-self-issued intermediate certificates that can follow the peer certificate in a valid certification path. So, if depth is 0 the PEER must be signed by the trusted ROOT-CA directly; if 1 the path can be PEER, CA, ROOT-CA; if 2 the path can be PEER, CA, CA, ROOT-CA, and so on. The default value is 10. Used to mitigate DoS attack possibilities.


.RE

{verify_fun,  Verify}
.RS 2
Customize certificate path validation

.PP
The verification fun is to be defined as follows:

.IP
.nf
fun(OtpCert :: #'OTPCertificate'{},
    Event, InitialUserState :: term()) ->
	{valid, UserState :: term()} |
	{fail, Reason :: term()} | {unknown, UserState :: term()}.

fun(OtpCert :: #'OTPCertificate'{}, DerCert :: public_key:der_encoded(),
    Event, InitialUserState :: term()) ->
	{valid, UserState :: term()} |
	{fail, Reason :: term()} | {unknown, UserState :: term()}.

Types:
      Event = {bad_cert, Reason :: atom() |
              {revoked, atom()}} |
		{extension, #'Extension'{}} |
              valid |
              valid_peer

.fi

.PP
The verification fun is called during the X.509-path validation when an error occurs or an extension unknown to the SSL application is encountered. It is also called when a certificate is considered valid by the path validation to allow access to each certificate in the path to the user application. It differentiates between the peer certificate and the CA certificates by using \fIvalid_peer\fR or \fIvalid\fR as \fIEvent\fR argument to the verification fun. See the Public_Key User's Guide for definition of \fI#'OTPCertificate'{}\fR and \fI#'Extension'{}\fR.


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If the verify callback fun returns \fI{fail, Reason}\fR, the verification process is immediately stopped, an alert is sent to the peer, and the TLS/DTLS handshake terminates.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If the verify callback fun returns \fI{valid, UserState}\fR, the verification process continues.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If the verify callback fun always returns \fI{valid, UserState}\fR, the TLS/DTLS handshake does not terminate regardless of verification failures, and the connection is established.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
If called with an extension unknown to the user application, the fun is to return \fI{unknown, UserState}\fR.

.RE

.PP
Note that if the fun returns \fIunknown\fR for an extension marked as critical, validation will fail.

.PP
Default option \fIverify_fun\fR in \fIverify_peer mode\fR:

.IP
.nf
{fun(_, _, {bad_cert, _} = Reason, _) ->
	 {fail, Reason};
    (_, _, {extension, _}, UserState) ->
	 {unknown, UserState};
    (_, _, valid, UserState) ->
	 {valid, UserState};
    (_, _, valid_peer, UserState) ->
       {valid, UserState}
 end, []}

.fi

.PP
Default option \fIverify_fun\fR in mode \fIverify_none\fR:

.IP
.nf
 {fun(_, _, {bad_cert, _}, UserState) ->
	 {valid, UserState};
    (_, _, {extension, #'Extension'{critical = true}}, UserState) ->
	 {valid, UserState};
    (_, _, {extension, _}, UserState) ->
	 {unknown, UserState};
    (_, _, valid, UserState) ->
	 {valid, UserState};
    (_, _, valid_peer, UserState) ->
       {valid, UserState}
 end, []}

.fi

.PP
The possible path validation errors are given in the form \fI{bad_cert, Reason}\fR, where \fIReason\fR is:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIunknown_ca\fR\fR

.PP
No trusted CA was found in the trusted store. The trusted CA is normally a so-called ROOT CA, which is a self-signed certificate. Trust can be claimed for an intermediate CA (the trusted anchor does not have to be self-signed according to X-509) by using option \fIpartial_chain\fR.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIselfsigned_peer\fR\fR

.PP
The chain consisted only of one self-signed certificate.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB{invalid_ext_keyusage, [public_key:oid()]} \fR

.PP
If the peer certificate specifies the extended keyusage extension and does not include the purpose for either being a TLS server (id-kp-ServerAuth) or TLS client (id-kp-ClientAuth) depending on the peers role.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB{ca_invalid_ext_keyusage, [public_key:oid()]} \fR

.PP
If a CA certificate specifies the extended keyusage extension and does not include the purpose for either being a TLS server (id-kp-ServerAuth) or TLS client (id-kp-ClientAuth) depending on the role of the peer chained with this CA, or the option allow_any_ca_purpose is set to \fItrue\fR but the special any-value (anyExtendedKeyUsage) is not included in the CA cert purposes.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIPKIX X-509-path validation error\fR\fR

.PP
For possible reasons, see \fIpublic_key:pkix_path_validation/3\fR.

.RE


.RE

{cert_policy_opts, PolicyOpts}
.RS 2
Handle certificate policies.

.PP
Configure X.509 certificate policy handling for the certificate path validation process; see public_key:pkix_path_validation/3 for more details.


.RE

{allow_any_ca_purpose, boolean()}
.RS 2
Handle certificate extended key usages extension

.PP
If a CA certificate has an extended key usage extension but it does not want to restrict the usages of the key it can include a special \fIanyExtendedKeyUsage\fR purpose. If this is option is set to \fItrue\fR all key usage purposes is automatically accepted for a CA that include that purpose, the options default to false.


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{crl_check, Check}\fR\fR  - Handle certificate revocation lists.

.PP
Perform CRL (Certificate Revocation List) verification (public_key:pkix_crls_validate/3) on all the certificates during the path validation (public_key:pkix_path_validation/3) of the certificate chain. \fICheck\fR defaults to \fIfalse\fR.

.PP
The meaning of \fICheck\fR is as follows:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIfalse\fR\fR

.PP
No checks are performed.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIpeer\fR\fR

.PP
Check is only performed on the peer certificate.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIbest_effort\fR\fR

.PP
If certificate revocation status cannot be determined it will be accepted as valid.

.PP
The CA certificates specified for the connection will be used to construct the certificate chain validating the CRLs.

.PP
The CRLs will be fetched from a local or external cache. See \fIssl_crl_cache_api\fR.

