\fB          {secure_renegotiate, SecureRenegotiate :: boolean()} |\fR
\fB          {user_lookup_fun, {Lookupfun :: fun(), UserState :: any()}}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Options common to client and server side prior to TLS-1.3.

{eccs, NamedCurves}
.RS 2
Named Elliptic Curves

.PP
Elliptic curves that can be used in pre TLS-1.3 key exchange.


.RE

{secure_renegotiate, SecureRenegotiate}
.RS 2
Inter-operate trade-off option

.PP
Specifies whether to reject renegotiation attempt that does not live up to RFC 5746. By default, \fISecureRenegotiate\fR is \fItrue\fR, meaning that secure renegotiation is enforced. If \fISecureRenegotiate\fR is \fIfalse\fR secure renegotiation will still be used if possible, but it falls back to insecure renegotiation if the peer does not support if RFC 5746.


.RE

{user_lookup_fun, {LookupFun, UserState}}
.RS 2
PSK/SRP cipher suite option

.PP
The lookup fun is to be defined as follows:

.IP
.nf
fun(psk, PSKIdentity :: binary(), UserState :: term()) ->
	{ok, SharedSecret :: binary()} | error;
fun(srp, Username :: binary(), UserState :: term()) ->
	{ok, {SRPParams :: srp_param_type(), Salt :: binary(),
	      DerivedKey :: binary()}} | error.

.fi

.PP
For Pre-Shared Key (PSK) cipher suites, the lookup fun is called by the client and server to determine the shared secret. When called by the client, \fIPSKIdentity\fR is the hint presented by the server or \fIundefined\fR. When called by the server, \fIPSKIdentity\fR is the identity presented by the client.

.PP
For Secure Remote Password (SRP), the fun is only used by the server to obtain parameters that it uses to generate its session keys. \fIDerivedKey\fR is to be derived according to RFC 2945 and RFC 5054: \fIcrypto:sha([Salt, crypto:sha([Username, <<$:>>, Password])])\fR


.RE


