.B
\fBsignature_algs() :: [{hash(), sign_algo()} | sign_scheme()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Explicitly list acceptable signature algorithms for certificates and handshake messages in the preferred order.

.PP
The client will send its list as the client hello \fIsignature_algorithm\fR extension introduced in TLS-1.2; see Section 7.4.1.4.1 in RFC 5246. Before TLS-1.2, these algorithms where implicitly chosen and partly derived from the cipher suite.

.PP
In TLS-1.2 a somewhat more explicit negotiation is made possible using a list of \fI{HashAlgo, SignAlgo}\fR tuples.

.PP
In TLS-1.3, these algorithm pairs are replaced by signature schemes that are completely decoupled from the cipher suite.

.PP
Signature algorithms used for certificates can be overridden by the signature schemes supplied by the \fIsignature_algs_cert\fR option.

.PP
The TLS-1.2 default is \fIDefault_TLS_12_Alg_Pairs\fR interleaved with \fIrsa_pss_schemes\fR since ssl-11.0 (Erlang/OTP 25). \fIpss_pss\fR is preferred over \fIpss_rsae\fR, which in turn is preferred over \fIrsa\fR.

.PP
The list for \fIDefault_TLS_12_Alg_Pairs\fR is defined as follows:

.IP
.nf
[
{sha512, ecdsa},
{sha512, rsa},
{sha384, ecdsa},
{sha384, rsa},
{sha256, ecdsa},
{sha256, rsa}
]

.fi

.RS 4
.PP
\fBChange \fR


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Support for \fI{md5, rsa}\fR was removed from the TLS-1.2 default in ssl-8.0 (Erlang/OTP 22).

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Support for \fI{sha, _}\fR (SHA1) and \fI{sha224, _}\fR was removed from the TLS-1.2 default in ssl-11.0 (Erlang/OTP 26).

.RE

.RE

.PP
The list for \fIrsa_pss_schemes\fR is defined as follows:

.IP
.nf
[rsa_pss_pss_sha512,
rsa_pss_pss_sha384,
rsa_pss_pss_sha256,
rsa_pss_rsae_sha512,
rsa_pss_rsae_sha384,
rsa_pss_rsae_sha256]

.fi

.PP
The list of \fITLS_13_Legacy_Schemes\fR is defined as follows:

.IP
.nf
[
%% Legacy algorithms only applicable to certificate signatures
rsa_pkcs1_sha512, %% Corresponds to {sha512, rsa}
rsa_pkcs1_sha384, %% Corresponds to {sha384, rsa}
rsa_pkcs1_sha256, %% Corresponds to {sha256, rsa}
]

.fi

.PP
The list of \fIDefault_TLS_13_Schemes\fR is defined as follows:

.IP
.nf
[
%% EDDSA
eddsa_ed25519,
eddsa_ed448

%% ECDSA
ecdsa_secp521r1_sha512,
ecdsa_secp384r1_sha384,
ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256] ++

%% RSASSA-PSS
rsa_pss_schemes()

.fi

.PP
\fBCHANGE: \fREDDSA was made highest priority in ssl-10.8 (Erlang/OTP 25).


.PP
The TLS-1.3 default is \fIDefault_TLS_13_Schemes\fR.

.PP
If both TLS-1.3 and TLS-1.2 are supported the default is:

.IP
.nf
Default_TLS_13_Schemes ++ TLS_13_Legacy_Schemes ++
Default_TLS_12_Alg_Pairs %% not represented in TLS_13_Legacy_Schemes

.fi

.PP
to ensure that appropriate algorithms can be chosen for the negotiated version.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.RE

.PP
TLS-1.2 algorithms will not be negotiated for TLS-1.3, but the TLS-1.3 RSASSA-PSS (\fIrsassa_pss_scheme()\fR) signature schemes can be negotiated also for TLS-1.2 from Erlang/OTP 24.1 (fully working from Erlang/OTP 24.1.3). However, if both TLS 1.3 and TLS 1.2 are supported using defaults, and TLS 1.3 is negotiated, the corresponding TLS 1.2 algorithms for TLS 1.3 legacy signature schemes will be treated as legacy schemes and applied only to certificate signatures.


.RE
.B
\fBsocket() :: gen_tcp:socket() | socket:socket().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A socket that can be used to perform a so-called "START-TLS", which means using an already connected socket previously used for plain TCP traffic and upgrading it to use TLS.

.PP
Both sides needs to agree on the upgrade.


