.br
.RS
.PP
TLS protocol version.


.RE
.B
\fBtransport_option() ::\fR
\fB          {cb_info,\fR
\fB           {CallbackModule :: atom(),\fR
\fB            DataTag :: atom(),\fR
\fB            ClosedTag :: atom(),\fR
\fB            ErrTag :: atom()}} |\fR
\fB          {cb_info,\fR
\fB           {CallbackModule :: atom(),\fR
\fB            DataTag :: atom(),\fR
\fB            ClosedTag :: atom(),\fR
\fB            ErrTag :: atom(),\fR
\fB            PassiveTag :: atom()}}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Transport option defines a callback module and message tags to handle the underlying transport socket.

.PP
Can be used to customize the transport layer. The tag values should be the values used by the underlying transport in its active mode messages.

.PP
Defaults to \fI{gen_tcp, tcp, tcp_closed, tcp_error, tcp_passive}\fR for TLS.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.RE

.PP
For backward compatibility a tuple of size four will be converted to a tuple of size five, where \fIPassiveTag\fR is the \fIDataTag\fR element with \fI_passive\fR appended.

.PP
For TLS the callback module must implement a reliable transport protocol, behave as \fIgen_tcp\fR, and have functions corresponding to \fIinet:setopts/2\fR, \fIinet:getopts/2\fR, \fIinet:peername/1\fR, \fIinet:sockname/1\fR, and \fIinet:port/1\fR. The callback \fIgen_tcp\fR is treated specially and calls \fIinet\fR directly. For DTLS this feature is considered experimental.


.RE
.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBappend_cipher_suites(Deferred, Suites) -> ciphers()\fR
\fB                              when\fR
\fB                                  Deferred ::\fR
\fB                                      ciphers() | cipher_filters(),\fR
\fB                                  Suites :: ciphers().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Make \fIDeferred\fR suites become the least preferred suites.

.PP
The \fIDeferred\fR suites will be put at the end of the cipher suite list \fISuites\fR after removing them from \fISuites\fR if present. \fIDeferred\fR can be a list of cipher suites or a list of filters in which case the filters are used on \fISuites\fR to extract the deferred cipher list.


.RE
.B
\fBcipher_suites(Description, Version) -> ciphers()\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Description ::\fR
\fB                               default | all | exclusive | anonymous |\fR
\fB                               exclusive_anonymous,\fR
\fB                           Version :: protocol_version().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Lists all available cipher suites corresponding to \fIDescription\fR.

.PP
The \fIexclusive\fR and \fIexclusive_anonymous\fR option will exclusively list cipher suites first supported in \fIVersion\fR, whereas the other options are inclusive from the lowest possible version to \fIVersion\fR. The \fIall\fR option includes all suites except anonymous suites. No anonymous suites are supported by default.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRTLS-1.3 has no overlapping cipher suites with previous TLS versions, meaning that the result of \fIcipher_suites(all, 'tlsv1.3')\fR contains a separate set of suites that can be used with TLS-1.3 and another set that can be used if a lower version is negotiated. The so-called \fIPSK\fR and \fISRP\fR suites (prior to TLS-1.3) need extra configuration to work; namely the option \fIuser_lookup_function\fR. No anonymous suites are supported by TLS-1.3. Also note that the cipher suites returned by this function are the cipher suites that the OTP SSL application can support provided that they are supported by the crypto library linked with the OTP Crypto application. Use \fIssl:filter_cipher_suites(Suites, [])\fR to filter the list for the current crypto library. Note that cipher suites may be filtered out because they are too old or too new depending on the crypto library.



.RE
.B
\fBcipher_suites(Description, Version, StringType) -> [string()]\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Description ::\fR
\fB                               default | all | exclusive | anonymous,\fR
\fB                           Version :: protocol_version(),\fR
\fB                           StringType :: rfc | openssl.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIcipher_suites/2\fR, but lists RFC or OpenSSL string names instead of \fIerl_cipher_suite()\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBclear_pem_cache() -> ok.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Clears the PEM cache.

.PP
PEM files, used by SSL API-functions, are cached for performance reasons. The cache is automatically checked at regular intervals to determine whether any cache entries should be invalidated.

.PP
This function provides a way to unconditionally clear the entire cache, thereby forcing a reload of previously cached PEM files.


.RE
.B
\fBclose(SslSocket) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when SslSocket :: sslsocket(), Reason :: any().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Closes a TLS/DTLS connection.


.RE
.B
\fBclose(SslSocket, How) ->\fR
\fB               ok | {ok, port()} | {ok, port(), Data} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                   How ::\fR
\fB                       timeout() | {NewController :: pid(), timeout()},\fR
\fB                   Data :: binary(),\fR
\fB                   Reason :: any().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Closes or downgrades a TLS connection.

.PP
In the latter case the transport connection will be handed over to the \fINewController\fR process after receiving the TLS close alert from the peer. The returned transport socket will have the following options set: \fI[{active, false}, {packet, 0}, {mode, binary}]\fR.

.PP
In case of downgrade, the close function might return some binary data that should be treated by the user as the first bytes received on the downgraded connection.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(TCPSocketOrHost, TLSOptionsOrPort, TimeoutOrTLSOptions) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, sslsocket()} |\fR
\fB                 {ok, sslsocket(), Ext :: protocol_extensions()} |\fR
\fB                 {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     TCPSocketOrHost :: socket() | host(),\fR
\fB                     TLSOptionsOrPort ::\fR
\fB                         [tls_client_option()] | inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                     TimeoutOrTLSOptions ::\fR
\fB                         [tls_client_option()] | timeout(),\fR
\fB                     Reason ::\fR
\fB                         closed | timeout |\fR
\fB                         {options, any()} |\fR
\fB                         error_alert() |\fR
\fB                         reason().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Opens a TLS/DTLS connection.

.IP
.nf
connect(TCPSocket, TLSOptions, Timeout).

.fi

.PP
Upgrades a \fIgen_tcp\fR (or equivalent) connected socket to a TLS socket by performing the client-side TLS handshake.

.IP
.nf
connect(Host, Port, TLSOptions).

.fi

.PP
Opens a TLS/DTLS connection to \fIHost\fR, \fIPort\fR. This call is equivalent to:

.IP
.nf
connect(Host, Port, TLSOptions, infinity).

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(Host, Port, TLSOptions, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, sslsocket()} |\fR
\fB                 {ok, sslsocket(), Ext :: protocol_extensions()} |\fR
\fB                 {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     Host :: host(),\fR
\fB                     Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                     TLSOptions :: [tls_client_option()],\fR
\fB                     Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                     Reason ::\fR
\fB                         closed | timeout |\fR
\fB                         {options, any()} |\fR
\fB                         error_alert() |\fR
\fB                         reason().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Opens a TLS/DTLS connection to \fIHost\fR, \fIPort\fR.

.PP
When the \fIverify\fR option is set to \fIverify_peer\fR, the \fIpublic_key:pkix_verify_hostname/2\fR check will be performed in addition to the usual X.509-path validation checks. If the check fails, the error \fI{bad_cert, hostname_check_failed}\fR will be propagated to the path validation fun, where it is possible to do customized checks by using the full possibilities of the \fIpublic_key:pkix_verify_hostname/3\fR API. When the \fIserver_name_indication\fR option is provided, its value (the DNS name) will be used as \fIReferenceID\fR to \fIpublic_key:pkix_verify_hostname/2\fR. When no \fIserver_name_indication\fR option is given, the \fIHost\fR argument will be used as Server Name Indication extension. The \fIHost\fR argument will also be used for the \fIpublic_key:pkix_verify_hostname/2\fR check. If the \fIHost\fR argument is an \fIinet:ip_address()\fR the \fIReferenceID\fR used for the check will be \fI{ip, Host}\fR; otherwise \fIdns_id\fR will be assumed with a fallback to \fIip\fR if that fails.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRAccording to good practices, certificates should not use IP addresses as "server names", especially outside a closed network.


.PP
If the \fI{handshake, hello}\fR option is used, the handshake is paused after receiving the server hello message and the success response is \fI{ok, SslSocket, Ext}\fR instead of \fI{ok, SslSocket}\fR. Thereafter the handshake is continued or canceled by calling \fIhandshake_continue/3\fR or \fIhandshake_cancel/1\fR.

.PP
If the \fIactive\fR option is set to \fIonce\fR, \fItrue\fR, or an integer value, the process owning the SSL socket will receive messages of type \fIactive_msgs()\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBconnection_information(SslSocket) ->\fR
\fB                                {ok, Result} | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                                when\fR
\fB                                    SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                                    Result :: connection_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the most relevant information about the connection.

.PP
Some items that are undefined will be filtered out. No values that affect the security of the connection will be returned.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe legacy \fIcipher_suite\fR item was removed in OTP 23. Previously it returned the cipher suite in its (undocumented) legacy format. It is replaced by \fIselected_cipher_suite\fR.



.RE
.B
\fBconnection_information(SslSocket, Items) ->\fR
\fB                                {ok, Result} | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                                when\fR
\fB                                    SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                                    Items :: connection_info_keys(),\fR
\fB                                    Result :: connection_info().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the requested information items about the connection if they are defined.

.PP
Note that the values for \fIclient_random\fR, \fIserver_random\fR, \fImaster_secret\fR, and \fIkeylog\fR affect the security of connection.

.PP
In order to retrieve \fIkeylog\fR information from a TLS connection, the \fIkeep_secrets\fR option must be configured in advance.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIf only undefined options are requested the resulting list can be empty.



.RE
.B
\fBcontrolling_process(SslSocket, NewController) ->\fR
\fB                             ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                             when\fR
\fB                                 SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                                 NewController :: pid(),\fR
\fB                                 Reason :: any().\fR

