.RE
.B
\fBgroups() -> [group()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns all supported groups in TLS 1.3.

.PP
Existed since OTP 22.0; documented as of OTP 27.


.RE
.B
\fBgroups(Description) -> [group()] when Description :: default.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns default supported groups in TLS 1.3.

.PP
Existed since OTP 22.0; documented as of OTP 27.


.RE
.B
\fBhandshake(HsSocket, OptionsOrTimeout) ->\fR
\fB                   {ok, SslSocket} |\fR
\fB                   {ok, SslSocket, Ext} |\fR
\fB                   {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                   when\fR
\fB                       HsSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                       OptionsOrTimeout :: timeout() | [server_option()],\fR
\fB                       SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                       Ext :: protocol_extensions(),\fR
\fB                       Reason :: closed | timeout | error_alert().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Performs the TLS/DTLS server-side handshake.

.PP
If the second argument is a timeout value:

.IP
.nf
handshake(HsSocket, Timeout).

.fi

.PP
this call is equivalent to:

.IP
.nf
handshake(HsSocket, [], Timeout).

.fi

.PP
Otherwise, if the second argument is a list of options:

.IP
.nf
handshake(HsSocket, Options).

.fi

.PP
this call is equivalent to:

.IP
.nf
handshake(HsSocket, Options, infinity).

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBhandshake(Socket, Options, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                   {ok, SslSocket} |\fR
\fB                   {ok, SslSocket, Ext} |\fR
\fB                   {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                   when\fR
\fB                       Socket :: socket() | sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                       SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                       Options :: [server_option() | common_option()],\fR
\fB                       Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                       Ext :: protocol_extensions(),\fR
\fB                       Reason ::\fR
\fB                           closed | timeout |\fR
\fB                           {options, any()} |\fR
\fB                           error_alert().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Performs the TLS/DTLS server-side handshake.

.PP
Returns a new TLS/DTLS socket if the handshake is successful.

.PP
If \fISocket\fR is a ordinary \fIsocket()\fR, upgrades a \fIgen_tcp\fR or equivalent socket to an SSL socket by performing the TLS server-side handshake and returning a TLS socket.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.RE

.PP
The ordinary \fISocket\fR must be in passive mode (\fI{active, false}\fR) before calling this function and before the client tries to connect with TLS; otherwise, the behavior of this function is undefined. The best way to ensure this is to create the ordinary listen socket in passive mode.

.PP
If \fISocket\fR is an \fIsslsocket()\fR, provides extra TLS/DTLS options to those specified in \fIlisten/2\fR and then performs the TLS/DTLS handshake. Returns a new TLS/DTLS socket if the handshake is successful.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBWarning \fR

.RE

.PP
Not setting the timeout makes the server more vulnerable to Denial of Service (DoS) attacks.

.PP
If option \fI{handshake, hello}\fR is specified the handshake is paused after receiving the client hello message and the success response is \fI{ok, SslSocket, Ext}\fR instead of \fI{ok, SslSocket}\fR. Thereafter the handshake is continued or canceled by calling \fIhandshake_continue/3\fR or \fIhandshake_cancel/1\fR.

.PP
If option \fIactive\fR is set to \fIonce\fR, \fItrue\fR, or an integer value, the process owning the \fIsslsocket()\fR will receive messages of type \fIactive_msgs()\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBhandshake_cancel(#sslsocket{}) -> any().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Cancel the handshake with a fatal \fIUSER_CANCELED\fR alert.


.RE
.B
\fBhandshake_continue(HsSocket, Options, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                            {ok, SslSocket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                            when\fR
\fB                                HsSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                                Options ::\fR
\fB                                    [client_option() |\fR
\fB                                     server_option() |\fR
\fB                                     common_option()],\fR
\fB                                Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                                SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                                Reason ::\fR
\fB                                    closed | timeout | error_alert().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Continue the TLS handshake, possibly with new, additional, or changed options.


.RE
.B
\fBlisten(Port, Options) -> {ok, ListenSocket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    Port :: inet:port_number(),\fR
\fB                    Options :: [tls_server_option()],\fR
\fB                    ListenSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: {options, any()} | reason().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Creates an SSL listen socket.


.RE
.B
\fBnegotiated_protocol(SslSocket) -> {ok, Protocol} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                             when\fR
\fB                                 SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                                 Protocol :: binary(),\fR
\fB                                 Reason ::\fR
\fB                                     protocol_not_negotiated | closed.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the protocol negotiated through ALPN or NPN extensions.


.RE
.B
\fBpeercert(SslSocket) -> {ok, Cert} | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                      Cert :: public_key:der_encoded().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The peer certificate is returned as a DER-encoded binary.

.PP
The certificate can be decoded with \fIpublic_key:pkix_decode_cert/2\fR. Suggested further reading about certificates is Public_Key User's Guide and SSL User's Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBpeername(SslSocket) -> {ok, {Address, Port}} | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                      Address :: inet:ip_address(),\fR
\fB                      Port :: inet:port_number().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the address and port number of the peer.


.RE
.B
\fBprepend_cipher_suites(Preferred, Suites) -> ciphers()\fR
\fB                               when\fR
\fB                                   Preferred ::\fR
\fB                                       ciphers() | cipher_filters(),\fR
\fB                                   Suites :: ciphers().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Make \fIPreferred\fR suites become the most preferred suites.

.PP
The \fIPreferred\fR suites will be put at the head of the cipher suite list \fISuites\fR after removing them from \fISuites\fR if present. \fIPreferred\fR can be a list of cipher suites or a list of filters in which case the filters are used on \fISuites\fR to extract the preferred cipher list.


.RE
.B
\fBprf(SslSocket, Secret, Label, Seed, WantedLength) ->\fR
\fB             {ok, binary()} | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB             when\fR
\fB                 SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                 Secret :: binary() | master_secret,\fR
\fB                 Label :: binary(),\fR
\fB                 Seed :: [binary() | prf_random()],\fR
\fB                 WantedLength :: non_neg_integer().\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: ssl:prf/5 is deprecated; Use export_key_materials/4 instead. Note that in OTP 28 the 'testing' way of calling this function will no longer be supported.
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Uses the Pseudo-Random Function (PRF) of a TLS session to generate extra key material.

.PP
It either takes user-generated values for \fISecret\fR and \fISeed\fR or atoms directing it to use a specific value from the session security parameters.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.RE

.PP
This function is replaced by \fIexport_key_materials/4\fR, the officially documented API function since OTP 27, which is equivalent to \fIprf(TLSSocket, master_secret, Label, [client_random, server_random, Context], WantedLength)\fR](\fIprf/5\fR). Other ways of calling this function were for testing purposes only and has no use case. When called in a TLS-1.3 context it will now behave as [\fIexport_key_materials(TLSSocket, [Label], [Context], [WantedLength])\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBrecv(SslSocket, Length, Timeout) -> {ok, Data} | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                  Length :: non_neg_integer(),\fR
\fB                  Data :: binary() | list() | HttpPacket,\fR
\fB                  Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                  HttpPacket :: any().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Receives a packet from a socket in passive mode.

.PP
A closed socket is indicated by return value \fI{error, closed}\fR. Argument \fILength\fR is meaningful only when the socket is in mode \fIraw\fR and denotes the number of bytes to read. If \fILength\fR is zero, all available bytes are returned. If \fILength\fR is greater than zero, exactly \fILength\fR bytes are returned, or an error; possibly discarding less than \fILength\fR bytes of data when the socket gets closed from the other side.

.PP
Optional argument \fITimeout\fR specifies a time-out in milliseconds. The default value is \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBrenegotiate(SslSocket) -> ok | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                     when SslSocket :: sslsocket().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Initiates a new handshake.

.PP
A notable return value is \fI{error, renegotiation_rejected}\fR indicating that the peer refused to go through with the renegotiation, but the connection is still active using the previously negotiated session.

.PP
TLS-1.3 has removed the renegotiation feature from earlier TLS versions and instead adds a new feature called key update, which replaces the most important part of renegotiation: the refreshing of session keys. This is triggered automatically after reaching a plaintext limit and can be configured using the \fIkey_update_at\fR option in \fIcommon_option_tls13/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsend(SslSocket, Data) -> ok | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB              when SslSocket :: sslsocket(), Data :: iodata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Writes \fIData\fR to \fISslSocket\fR.

.PP
A notable return value is \fI{error, closed}\fR indicating that the socket is closed.


.RE
.B
\fBsetopts(SslSocket, Options) -> ok | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                     Options :: [gen_tcp:option()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Sets options according to \fIOptions\fR for socket \fISslSocket\fR.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBNote \fR

.RE

.PP
Note that setting low level transport protocol specific options may or may not work in a TLS-environment. And even if they work it may make your code platform specific, or stop working in later version of this application. Such options could make sense for some special corner cases although it is not a general viable option. Such trade-offs must be carefully considered by the user that need to fully understand the consequences of setting such options.


.RE
.B
\fBshutdown(SslSocket, How) -> ok | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                      How :: read | write | read_write.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Immediately closes a socket in one or two directions.

.PP
\fIHow == write\fR means closing the socket for writing, but reading from it is still possible.

.PP
To handle siutations where the peer has performed a shutdown on the write side, option \fI{exit_on_close, false}\fR is useful.


.RE
.B
\fBsignature_algs(Description, Version) -> signature_algs()\fR
\fB                        when\fR
\fB                            Description :: default | all | exclusive,\fR
\fB                            Version :: protocol_version().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Lists all available signature algorithms corresponding to \fIDescription\fR.

.PP
The \fIexclusive\fR option will exclusively list algorithms or algorithm schemes for that protocol version, whereas the \fIdefault\fR and \fIall\fR options lists the combined list to support the range of protocols from (D)TLS-1.2, the first version to support configuration of the signature algorithms, to \fIVersion\fR.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> ssl:signature_algs(default, 'tlsv1.3').
[eddsa_ed25519,eddsa_ed448,ecdsa_secp521r1_sha512,
 ecdsa_secp384r1_sha384,ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256,
 ecdsa_brainpoolP512r1tls13_sha512,
 ecdsa_brainpoolP384r1tls13_sha384,
 ecdsa_brainpoolP256r1tls13_sha256,rsa_pss_pss_sha512,
 rsa_pss_pss_sha384,rsa_pss_pss_sha256,rsa_pss_rsae_sha512,
 rsa_pss_rsae_sha384,rsa_pss_rsae_sha256,mldsa44,mldsa65,
 mldsa87,rsa_pkcs1_sha512,rsa_pkcs1_sha384,rsa_pkcs1_sha256,
 {sha512,ecdsa},
 {sha384,ecdsa},
 {sha256,ecdsa}]

2> ssl:signature_algs(all, 'tlsv1.3').
[eddsa_ed25519,eddsa_ed448,ecdsa_secp521r1_sha512,ecdsa_secp384r1_sha384,
 ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256,ecdsa_brainpoolP512r1tls13_sha512,
 ecdsa_brainpoolP384r1tls13_sha384,ecdsa_brainpoolP256r1tls13_sha256,
 rsa_pss_pss_sha512,rsa_pss_pss_sha384,rsa_pss_pss_sha256,rsa_pss_rsae_sha512,
 rsa_pss_rsae_sha384,rsa_pss_rsae_sha256,mldsa44,mldsa65,mldsa87,
 rsa_pkcs1_sha512,rsa_pkcs1_sha384,rsa_pkcs1_sha256,
 {sha512,ecdsa},
 {sha384,ecdsa},
 {sha256,ecdsa},
 slh_dsa_shake_256f,slh_dsa_shake_256s,slh_dsa_sha2_256f,slh_dsa_sha2_256s,
 slh_dsa_shake_192f,slh_dsa_shake_192s,slh_dsa_sha2_192f,slh_dsa_sha2_192s,
 slh_dsa_shake_128f,slh_dsa_shake_128s,slh_dsa_sha2_128f,slh_dsa_sha2_128s,
 ecdsa_sha1,rsa_pkcs1_sha1,
 {sha224,ecdsa},
 {sha224,rsa},
 {sha,dsa}]

3> [ssl:signature_algs(exclusive, 'tlsv1.3').
[eddsa_ed25519,eddsa_ed448,ecdsa_secp521r1_sha512,ecdsa_secp384r1_sha384,
 ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256,ecdsa_brainpoolP512r1tls13_sha512,
 ecdsa_brainpoolP384r1tls13_sha384,ecdsa_brainpoolP256r1tls13_sha256,
 rsa_pss_pss_sha512,rsa_pss_pss_sha384,rsa_pss_pss_sha256,rsa_pss_rsae_sha512,
 rsa_pss_rsae_sha384,rsa_pss_rsae_sha256,mldsa44,mldsa65,mldsa87,
 rsa_pkcs1_sha512,rsa_pkcs1_sha384,rsa_pkcs1_sha256,slh_dsa_shake_256f,
 slh_dsa_shake_256s,slh_dsa_sha2_256f,slh_dsa_sha2_256s,slh_dsa_shake_192f,
 slh_dsa_shake_192s,slh_dsa_sha2_192f,slh_dsa_sha2_192s,slh_dsa_shake_128f,
 slh_dsa_shake_128s,slh_dsa_sha2_128f,slh_dsa_sha2_128s]

.fi

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRSome TLS-1-3 scheme names overlap with TLS-1.2 algorithm-tuple-pair-names and then TLS-1.3 names will be used, for example \fIrsa_pkcs1_sha256\fR instead of \fI{sha256, rsa}\fR. These are legacy algorithms in TLS-1.3 that apply only to certificate signatures in this version of the protocol.



.RE
.B
\fBsockname(SslSocket) -> {ok, {Address, Port}} | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                      Address :: inet:ip_address(),\fR
\fB                      Port :: inet:port_number().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the local address and port number of socket \fISslSocket\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBstart(permanent | transient | temporary) -> ok | {error, reason()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Starts the SSL application.


.RE
.B
\fBstop() -> ok.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Stops the SSL application.


.RE
.B
\fBstr_to_suite(CipherSuiteName) ->\fR
\fB                      erl_cipher_suite() |\fR
\fB                      {error, {not_recognized, CipherSuiteName}}\fR
\fB                      when CipherSuiteName :: string().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Converts an RFC or OpenSSL name string to an \fIerl_cipher_suite/0\fR

.PP
Returns an error if the cipher suite is not supported or the name is not a valid cipher suite name.


.RE
.B
\fBsuite_to_openssl_str(CipherSuite) -> string()\fR
\fB                              when CipherSuite :: erl_cipher_suite().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Converts an \fIerl_cipher_suite()\fR value to an OpenSSL name string.

.PP
PRE TLS-1.3 these names differ for RFC names


.RE
.B
\fBsuite_to_str(CipherSuite) -> string()\fR
\fB                      when CipherSuite :: erl_cipher_suite().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Converts an \fIerl_cipher_suite()\fR value to an RFC name string.


.RE
.B
\fBtransport_accept(ListenSocket, Timeout) ->\fR
\fB                          {ok, SslSocket} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                          when\fR
\fB                              ListenSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                              Timeout :: timeout(),\fR
\fB                              SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                              Reason :: reason().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Accepts an incoming connection request on a listen socket.

.PP
\fIListenSocket\fR must be a socket returned from \fIlisten/2\fR. The socket returned is to be passed to \fIhandshake/1,2,3\fR to complete the handshake and establish the TLS/DTLS connection.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRMost API functions require that the TLS/DTLS connection is established to work as expected.


.PP
The accepted socket inherits the options set for \fIListenSocket\fR in \fIlisten/2\fR.

.PP
The default value for \fITimeout\fR is \fIinfinity\fR. If \fITimeout\fR is specified and no connection is accepted within the given time, \fI{error, timeout}\fR is returned.


.RE
.B
\fBupdate_keys(SslSocket, Type) -> ok | {error, reason()}\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         SslSocket :: sslsocket(),\fR
\fB                         Type :: write | read_write.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create new session keys.

.PP
There are cryptographic limits on the amount of plaintext which can be safely encrypted under a given set of keys. If the amount of data surpasses those limits, a key update is triggered and a new set of keys are installed. See also the \fIkey_update_at\fR option in \fIcommon_option_tls13/0\fR.

.PP
This function can be used to explicitly start a key update on a TLS-1.3 connection. There are two types of key updates: if \fIType\fR is \fIwrite\fR, only the writing key is updated; if \fIType\fR is \fIread_write\fR, both the reading and writing keys are updated.


.RE
.B
\fBversions() -> [VersionInfo]\fR
\fB                  when\fR
\fB                      VersionInfo ::\fR
\fB                          {ssl_app, string()} |\fR
\fB                          {supported | available | implemented,\fR
\fB                           [tls_version()]} |\fR
\fB                          {supported_dtls | available_dtls |\fR
\fB                           implemented_dtls,\fR
\fB                           [dtls_version()]}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Lists information, mainly concerning TLS/DTLS versions, in runtime for debugging and testing purposes.

app_vsn
.RS 2
The application version of the SSL application.


.RE

supported
.RS 2
TLS versions supported with current application environment and crypto library configuration. Overridden by a version option on 
\fIconnect/2,3,4\fR, \fIlisten/2\fR, and \fIhandshake/2,3\fR. For the negotiated TLS version, see \fIconnection_information/1\fR.

.RE

supported_dtls
.RS 2
DTLS versions supported with current application environment and crypto library configuration. Overridden by a version option on 
\fIconnect/2,3,4\fR, \fIlisten/2\fR, and \fIhandshake/2,3\fR. For the negotiated DTLS version, see \fIconnection_information/1\fR.

.RE

available
.RS 2
All TLS versions supported with the linked crypto library.


.RE

available_dtls
.RS 2
All DTLS versions supported with the linked crypto library.


.RE

implemented
.RS 2
All TLS versions supported by the SSL application if linked with a crypto library with the necessary support.


.RE

implemented_dtls
.RS 2
All DTLS versions supported by the SSL application if linked with a crypto library with the necessary support.


.RE


.RE
